Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon River are decorated with the motto: "The sea is our right.
It is our duty to recover it".
Across landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the lost coast now in the hands of Chile after a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the desire to once again traverse the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes have perhaps reached their highest level in decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and is obviously waiting for the result with a positive attitude", explained Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will be watching the International Court of Justice ruling on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will favourably accept Bolivia's claim that - after decades of intermittent dialogue - Chile is obliged to negotiate, guaranteeing Bolivia an outlet on the sea under state jurisdiction.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president - who is facing a controversial re-election battle next year - has a lot at stake with Monday's ruling.
"We are very close to our return to the Pacific Ocean", he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts feel that the court is unlikely to rule in Bolivia's favor and that little would change if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to assign the Chilean territory and has said it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the International Court of Justice's ruling comes just six months after the final arguments indicates that the case was "not complicated", said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from advancing the Bolivian cause, the past four years may have delayed it.
"The problem of access to the sea has been monopolized by the current Bolivian administration", said Zárate.
Morale's belligerent rhetoric has torpedoed any remaining goodwill in Chile, he suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be very difficult to maintain the discussions after what has happened.
The two countries haven't exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative at the Hague, rejected the idea that the tribunal's decision-making process was particularly expeditious.
On Monday, Bolivia will "have an extraordinary opportunity in relations with Chile" and will have the chance to "end 139 years of disagreements to mutual advantage", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - is using the maritime issue as a political ploy.
"Bolivia will never renounce its right to have access to the Pacific Ocean", he added.
"The ruling is an opportunity to see that we need to move beyond the past".
