Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons employees gave for the difficulty of filling jobs were due in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
This is why language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were not able to speak a foreign language at a level sufficient to be able to hold a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%.
That's why investing in language learning is so important for children today.
Knowing more languages, especially those from developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are deemed most important for the UK looking to 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be several languages to choose from in independent schools, with specialist teaching staff.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future may be.
There is no denying that in a global trading system today, languages are still crucial to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
I'll have to do it.
