'We do not see any corresponding response from the US,' he said.
"Without trust in the United States there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm unilaterally first".
Although Ri re-used the well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to "phased denuclearization" that would reward North Korea with gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization outright as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever full-fledged meeting between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal agreement to end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need to 'have denuclearization first' and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner and even oppose the 'declaration of the end of the war,' Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust".
Ri did not refer to plans for a second Kim-Trump summit that the US leader announced at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past 5 months and added: "If the counterpart of this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be dead at this point".
But even so, the tone of Ri's speech was noticeably different from last year's speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to target the US mainland with North Korean missiles after the evil President Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in pursuing disarmament, but said much more needed to be done and that sanctions would remain in place until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no deadline, saying that "whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
