What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that features a remarkable parade of stars and has an equally remarkable mission: to end world poverty.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people flock to the Great Lawn of Central Park to not only enjoy performances by Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also raise awareness about the event's real purpose, which is to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eliminate poverty by increasing the number of people who actively fight it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless you were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers had to complete a number of tasks, or "actions" such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or any other meaningful way that would help raise awareness about their goal of eliminating poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, precisely, now that it's 12 years away from reaching its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really a genuine way to persuade people to request a call to action, or is it just another example of so-called clicktivism - people who feel they are really making a difference by simply signing an online petition or tweeting?
Since 2011, Global Citizen says it has registered more than 19 million actions by its supporters, and used them for a variety of purposes.
It states that these actions have helped to urge world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, designed to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements stemming from their actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or used as funds.
The group estimates that hedge funds have so far directly impacted some 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor and developer partnership committed to "helping children grow to their full potential", pledging to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens just like you, we can make social injustice or malnutrition a footnote in history", The Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions calling on the UK to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government has announced funding for a project, Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children through nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the FAQs on their website, they asked: "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen responded: It will be a long and arduous journey - sometimes we will fall and fail.
But, like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
