Germany 's new warship has been delayed again
According to local media, the last frigate of the German Navy was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old military ships of the Cold War, but it will not be until at least next year due to faulty systems and increased costs.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper citing a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but troubling issues following delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old ships of the Bremen class.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as miniaturized radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, as it should be possible to deploy new frigates for up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continuing delays mean that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its power overseas, will already be obsolete when they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated Type F-125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have noted a number of crucial "software and hardware" flaws that made the ship unusable if used in a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be manned by a crew of about 120 sailors, just half the staff of the older Bremen-class ships.
In addition, it was found that the ship weighs significantly too much, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The Rheinland-Pfalz, at 7,000 tons, is believed to be twice as heavy as ships of similar classes used by the Germans in World War II.
Apart from the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) is also becoming an important issue.
It seems to have reached €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion) from the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems of the new frigates are becoming particularly important in the light of recent alarms about the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, Parliamentary Commissioner for the Armed Forces, admitted that the Navy was actually 'lacking ships that could be used'.
The official said that the issue has worsened considerably over time, as the old, disarmed ships have not been replaced by new ships.
His regret is that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates has been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust is spying on the secret life of bats
New research on a Highland farm in Scotland aims to reveal how bats use their eyes to find food.
