The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats, as well as brown-eared bats and Daubenton's bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using portable detectors.
An expert's analysis of the recorded sounds will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and the way each species behaves.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed scale picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the findings will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands, and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the past century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work affecting the three-pole and ruining the habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can mosquito-repellent paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles along their path.
LNTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the three-pointers, and occasionally perform rescues.
The organisation has even established Scotland's first bat-only reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says the property is ideal territory.
"Here in Threave we have a vast area for bats", he said.
We have the old buildings, many centuries-old trees and a good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats that we don't know yet, so the work we're doing here and at other properties is going to help us understand more about their growth needs.
It emphasises the importance of controlling bats before carrying out maintenance on properties as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single mother litter can kill up to 400 females and young, possibly wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their trespoles.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He stated: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are doing".
